06545nam a22010575i 9780823299669DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232996697 a10.1515/97808232996692doi  a(DE-B1597)624064  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aImagistic Care :bGrowing Old in a Precarious World /ced. by Cheryl Mattingly, Lone Grøn. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b16 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThinking from Elsewhere00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: Imagistic Inquiries: Old Age, Intimate Others, and Care -- tThe Gift: An Imagistic Critical Phenomenology -- tVirtuous Aging in Uncanny Moral Worlds: Being Old and Kyrgyz in the Absence of the Young -- t“Yeah . . . Yeah”: Imagistic Signatures and Responsive Events in a Danish Dementia Ward -- tOn the Silent Anarchy of Intimacy: Images of Alterity, Openness, and Sociality in Life with Dementia -- tTogether Apart: Fence Work in Landscapes of Relationality, Old Age, and Care in the Ik Mountains -- tImagining Self and Other: Carers, TV, and Touch -- tVirtues and Vexations: Intimate Others Caring for Elders in Eastern Uganda -- tThe Staircase: The Ethics of “Transcendence and Height” in Welfare Care -- tThe Drawing Underneath -- tAfterword: These Images Burn -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImagistic Care explores ethnographically how the images function in our concepts, our writing, our fieldwork, and our lives. With contributions from anthropologists, philosophers and an artist, the volume asks: How can imagistic inquiries help us understand the complex entanglements of self and other, dependence and independency, frailty and charisma, notions of good and bad aging, and norms and practices of care in old age? And how can imagistic inquiries offer grounds for critique? Cutting between ethnography, phenomenology and art, this volume offers a powerful contribution to understandings of growing old. The images created in words and drawings are used to complicate rather than simplify the world. The authors advance an understanding of care, and of aging itself, marked by alterity, spectral presences and uncertainty.Contributors: Rasmus Dyring, Harmandeep Kaur Gill, Lone Grøn, Maria Louw, Cheryl Mattingly, Lotte Meinert, Maria Speyer, Helle S. Wentzer, Susan Reynolds Whyte  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAgingvCross-cultural studies. 0aAgingxSocial aspects. 0aOlder peoplexCare. 0aOlder peoplexSocial conditions. 0aVisual anthropology. 0aVisual sociology. 4aAnthropology. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aHealth & Medicine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAging.  aAnthropology.  aArt.  aCare.  aEthics.  aImagination.  aImagistic Approaches.  aIntersubjectivity.  aPhenomenology.  aPhilosophy.1 aDesjarlais, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyring, Rasmus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrøn, Lone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrøn, Lone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaur Gill, Harmandeep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLouw, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattingly, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattingly, Cheryl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeinert, Lotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat